Progress to date
****************

Features implemented so far are

Utilities:

to expand tabs, convert ascii <-> ebcdic, convert fixed format
records to variable format and convert between DOS and Unix text
formats.

Preprocessor (blipre) to handle:

- line continuations
- copy and replace verbs
- comment-entries

Main compiler (blicc1):

Grammar for nucleus level 2 and a few other features. Including all
the hacks to get bison to recognise the BLISS grammar. See blicprs.tpl
for details.

I have most of the so-called compiler subset working now. See
blicprs.tpl for details of the compiler subset. What is left to do is
CALL/FUNCTIONS. This subset will be sufficient to write the remaining
runtime routines in this subset of BLISS.

Some of the runtime routines for other nucleus functions are done such
as move edited, unedit, string, unstring, inspect.

Features not implemented
************************

Most of bliss. See the bliss.texi file.

Objective:
**********

Full BLISS 85 implementation with selective extensions from specific
BLISS implementations and from the draft BLISS 2002 standard. 

Building Instructions:
**********************

See the bliss.texi file (find 'installation').

Note that you need the latest GCC snapshot to do a successful build
(ie the latest weekly snapshot).. See blicc1.c for details of the
latest snapshot used by the current source.

Credits
*******

AUTHORS has the credits. 

Contributors are welcome
************************

See the bliss.texi file. Main points being: every piece of code must
have an automated test; GNU coding standards are used - meaningful
variable names + comments detailing the interface to each function
(see file CODINGSTDS).

Send bug reports, fixes, enhancements. 
